Working with the Raw data type in 'R'

Mar 8, 2015

Of the six atomic vector types in ‘R’, the one least often discussed would arguably be ‘raw’. In fact many ‘R’ books of the tutorial or learning category only briefly mention its existence and discuss it no further.

So what is the ‘raw’ type and how is it used in R scripts? For readers already versed in the declarative language of SQL, the BLOB type can be considered equivalent with the ‘R’ raw type. In both cases the language treats the type as an opaque sequence of bytes and nothing more. It is only the enclosing application that knows how to interpret the sequence of bytes and the operations that may be performed upon it.

Raw type (and hence BLOB) type are often encodings of images or audio. These types have well know encodings and presentations. It is the programer who writes the program that knows the underlying type of the raw sequence of bytes and hence knows the containers objects that can be initialized with the data and manipulate it by image operations and presentations, or audio playback.

Specific instances of raw data types discussed thus far are well known industry standard types, but the raw type may be used in infinate ways to hold data structures that are unique to the application. In such cases, there may not be an industry standard encoding or representation outside of the application or vertical market.

With this article I hope to show readers the primary function for decoding an ‘R’ raw data type with an example that I found myself challended with. In this example we will be decoding a raw sequence of bytes from a SQLite database that are encoded as a seqence of 1300 single precision floating point variables. The floating point values are generated from measuring a substance with a Raman spectrometer, and storing the binary sequence from an Intel x86 little-endian architecture to a SQLite BLOB type.

The ‘R’ gem for handling raw (aka binary ) data is readBin and comes from the R base package.

Description Read binary data from a connection, or write binary data to a connection.

Usage

readBin(con, what, n = 1L, size = NA_integer_, signed = TRUE, endian = .Platform$endian)

The reader is encouraged to read the built in documentation from the system help. For completeness I’ve added the following code which reads the BLOB data from the SQLite table and thus converting the BLOB type to its equivalent ‘R’ raw type. At this point it is still opaque data.

#Load relavent libraries
library(RSQLite)
library(magrittr)
suppressMessages(library(dplyr))
library(ggplot2)

#Query the training spectrum from SQLite database
sqlQry <- paste0("SELECT LIB.[name], TR.[SpectrumIntensitiesNist], ",
                   "FROM Library AS LIB ",
                   "JOIN TrainingSpectra AS TR ON LIB.LibId = TR.LibId")

conn <- dbConnect(SQLite(), "~/Documents/training.db")
res = dbSendQuery(conn, sqlQry)
myTbl <- dbFetch(res)

dbDisconnect(conn)

Transform the data to tidy dataframe of numeric variables

So far all we have done is to read a table of two column data where one of the data types is a string representing the name of the substance and the other is a raw data type; aka opaque sequence of bytes.

This is not in a Tidy format. What we want is to convert the SQL data such that every column has it’s column name as the substance name string and each row is an intensity vs waveshift value. The x axis waveshift values are:

The dataframe to be generated will use our new friend the readBin function to create the columns of spectrum intensity values for each of the 1300 wave shifts.

Let us look at the 

# Create data frame
nistOnlyLibrary <- myTbl %>% {
    z <- mapply(
        function(x){
            # single precision type is 4 bytes in size
            # there are 1300 of them, in little-endian 
            # order to be converted to 'R's native 
            # double precision of 8 bytes per type.
            readBin(x, n=1300, numeric(),  size=4)
            },
        .$SpectrumIntensitiesNist)
    colnames(z) <- .$Name
    # The 1300 intensity values are over thethe raman shift
    # range of 501 to 1800.
    z <- cbind(501:1800, z)
} %>% {
    colnames(.)[1] <- 'waveshift'
    as.data.frame(.)
} %>%
    filter(waveshift > 510 & waveshift < 1790)

POST processing and inspection.

for (substance in names(nistOnlyLibrary[,2:192])){
    nistOnly <- ggplot(nistOnlyLibrary, 
                       aes(x = waveshift, y=nistOnlyLibrary[,substance]) ) +
        geom_line( col="blue") +
        labs(x="Raman waveshift", y="Intensity (NIST Corrected)") +
        ggtitle(drug)

    print(nistOnly)
}
